# 4. Source-of-Truth Model

Clearly separate desired intent, runtime representation, actual state, and history.

## 4.1 Desired-state source of truth

The portable, persistent, Git-friendly desired-state source of truth is:

```text
infrastructure.iis.yaml
```

This file:

* Is generated and maintained by the platform
* Can be committed to Git
* Can be reviewed in pull requests
* Can be generated from natural language, forms, IDE commands, or direct editing
* Can be consumed by any conformant implementation
* Must not contain credentials or sensitive state
* Must produce a stable normalized representation

Although direct editing must remain supported, ordinary users should not need to write IIS manually.

## 4.2 Canonical runtime representation

The **Canonical Infrastructure Model**, or CIM, is the normalized in-memory representation created from the IIS document.

The CIM contains:

* Normalized resources
* Resolved defaults
* Resource kinds and versions
* Relationships
* Derived dependencies
* Effective profiles
* Effective policies
* Provider-independent constraints
* Abstract outputs
* Validation metadata
* Provenance for generated and user-supplied values

All planning and analysis components operate on the CIM rather than raw YAML.

The CIM is canonical during processing, but the portable desired-state artifact remains the IIS document.

## 4.3 Actual infrastructure state

Maintain a separate, system-owned state artifact or state backend.

It stores:

* Provider resource identifiers
* Provider resource types
* Account, subscription, project, cluster, and region bindings
* Last observed configuration
* Last successfully applied desired-state hash
* Provider API versions
* Resource lifecycle status
* Outputs
* Dependency bindings
* Deployment identifiers
* Drift information
* Imported resources
* Sensitive references, never plaintext secrets
* Lock and concurrency metadata

State must never be embedded in the IIS document.

## 4.4 Immutable execution history

Every plan and deployment must generate an immutable record containing:

* Input IIS hash
* Canonical model hash
* Effective profile and policy hashes
* Provider mapping versions
* Plan
* Approvals
* Actor identity
* Timestamps
* Resources created, changed, replaced, imported, or destroyed
* Cost impact
* Security and compliance findings
* Execution logs
* Rollback result
* Verification result
* State version before and after deployment

