# 5. Non-Negotiable Architectural Principles

## 5.1 Intent over implementation

The IIS core describes outcomes and constraints, not cloud products or imperative steps.

## 5.2 Users do not need to learn IIS syntax

Natural language, guided forms, IDE actions, and visual design are normal authoring methods.

Direct IIS editing is an advanced, optional workflow.

## 5.3 AI never executes infrastructure

AI may:

* Understand natural language
* Extract intent
* Identify missing details
* Generate clarification questions
* Propose IIS modifications
* Explain plans
* Explain cost, security, and compliance findings
* Generate documentation
* Suggest improvements

AI must never:

* Call provider mutation APIs
* Apply a deployment plan
* Change actual state
* Bypass validation
* Bypass policy
* Approve its own plan
* Select destructive behavior without explicit deterministic rules
* Invent unsupported provider parameters
* Infer required production decisions silently

## 5.4 Deterministic execution

Once the IIS document is finalized, execution must not depend on AI, an LLM, MCP availability, or conversational history.

The same inputs and component versions must produce the same normalized model and execution plan.

Determinism inputs include:

* IIS document
* Profile versions
* Policy versions
* Extension versions
* Provider mapping version
* Provider discovery snapshot
* Pricing snapshot where relevant
* Planner version
* Explicit deployment target

## 5.5 Fail closed

Planning and deployment must stop when:

* Required intent is unresolved
* A mapping is incomplete
* A provider capability is unsupported
* Policy validation fails
* A required authoritative check cannot be completed
* State locking fails
* Drift creates an unsafe plan
* A destructive operation lacks approval
* A resource mapping would weaken declared intent

## 5.6 Provider logic does not leak into the core

AWS, Azure, GCP, Kubernetes, Cloudflare, and on-premises behavior belongs in provider mappings and namespaced extensions.

## 5.7 Plans are inspectable

Every planned resource and provider parameter must be traceable to:

* A user-supplied intent
* An explicit default
* A profile
* A policy
* A provider mapping rule
* A provider discovery result
* An approved recommendation

## 5.8 No hidden defaults

Every applied default must have:

* A stable identifier
* A source
* A version
* An explanation
* A visible representation in the plan
* An option to override where policy permits

## 5.9 The diagram is derived

Architecture diagrams, network diagrams, security diagrams, dependency views, and data-flow views must be generated from the same canonical model used for planning.

Manual diagrams must never be treated as a source of truth.

