# Phase 3 — Intent Authoring Engine and Intent Compiler

## Objective

Allow users to create and modify IIS without learning its syntax.

This phase introduces AI-assisted authoring but does not introduce deployment.

## Core rule

The LLM must never directly write arbitrary YAML into the source-of-truth file.

The expected pipeline is:

```text
Natural language
→ Intent extraction
→ Structured compiler operations
→ Validation
→ Canonical model mutation
→ Deterministic serialization
→ IIS document
```

## 3.1 Compiler operation model

Define typed operations such as:

```text
CreateResource
UpdateResource
RemoveResource
CreateRelationship
UpdateRelationship
RemoveRelationship
ApplyProfile
RemoveProfile
AddPolicy
ChangeConstraint
SetMetadata
SetExtensionValue
```

Each operation contains:

* Operation identifier
* Target
* Requested change
* Source input span
* Confidence
* Assumptions
* Required clarifications
* Provenance
* Validation result
* Preview diff

The compiler applies only validated operations.

## 3.2 Intent extraction

Extract:

* Environment
* Workload type
* Applications
* Data services
* Messaging
* Networking intent
* Exposure
* Identity
* Secrets
* Availability
* Scaling
* Regions or geography
* Backup
* RPO and RTO
* Security requirements
* Compliance frameworks
* Budget
* Operational requirements
* Provider preference
* Existing-resource constraints

## 3.3 Clarification engine

Ask questions only when:

* A required field cannot be deterministically defaulted
* Multiple interpretations materially change architecture
* Cost or availability choices conflict
* A destructive update is requested
* A compliance requirement requires missing scope information
* Provider selection is required
* An existing-resource reference is unresolved
* The request conflicts with policy

Questions must be:

* Minimal
* Contextual
* Grouped logically
* Accompanied by recommended defaults
* Accompanied by impact explanations
* Answerable through UI controls as well as text

Example:

> You requested high availability and a monthly limit of $300. A multi-zone relational database may exceed that budget. Choose one: raise the budget, use standard availability, or use a lower-cost database class.

## 3.4 Confidence and provenance

Every generated field must indicate whether it came from:

* Explicit user input
* Confirmed clarification
* Organization profile
* Policy
* IIS default
* Provider mapping default
* AI recommendation accepted by the user

Do not silently treat low-confidence AI output as intent.

## 3.5 Existing-document updates

Support commands such as:

* Add a cache for the API
* Make the database private
* Reduce expected cost
* Add disaster recovery
* Remove public access
* Move to maximum availability
* Add PCI DSS controls
* Explain what changes this request will make

Generate a semantic diff before saving.

## 3.6 Model-provider abstraction

Do not couple the compiler to a single LLM vendor.

Provide:

* Model adapter interface
* Structured-output schema
* Retry and repair rules
* Token and cost limits
* Redaction hooks
* Local-model option
* Data residency configuration
* Prompt versioning
* Evaluation harness

## 3.7 Intent compiler evaluation

Create a benchmark dataset covering:

* Clear requirements
* Ambiguous requirements
* Conflicting constraints
* Missing information
* Unsupported capabilities
* Provider-specific requests
* Incremental edits
* Destructive requests
* Security-sensitive requests
* Cost-sensitive requests
* Compliance requests

Measure:

* Correct resource extraction
* Correct relationship extraction
* Clarification precision
* Unsupported-feature detection
* False assumptions
* IIS validity
* Semantic equivalence
* Deterministic serialization after confirmation

## Deliverables

* Intent compiler SDK
* Compiler operation schema
* Clarification engine
* Provenance model
* AI adapter interface
* Prompt registry
* Evaluation suite
* Natural-language authoring prototype

## Exit criteria

* Natural-language requests can generate valid IIS for all official examples.
* No unvalidated LLM-generated YAML is written to disk.
* Low-confidence fields require confirmation.
* The same confirmed structured operations produce the same IIS regardless of the model originally used.
* The compiler cannot call deployment APIs.
* Every generated field has provenance.

