# 16. Final Success Criteria

The IIS ecosystem is successful when all of the following are true:

1. A user can describe infrastructure in natural language without learning IIS syntax.
2. The platform asks only necessary clarification questions.
3. The confirmed requirement generates a valid, portable `infrastructure.iis.yaml`.
4. The IIS document is the Git-friendly desired-state source of truth.
5. The Canonical Infrastructure Model provides a deterministic runtime representation.
6. Provider-independent intent is cleanly separated from provider configuration.
7. The same IIS document can map to multiple providers where capabilities are equivalent.
8. Identical inputs produce identical canonical models and plans.
9. AI, LLMs, and MCP are absent from the execution path.
10. Every provider value is explainable and traceable.
11. Architecture, dependencies, cost, security, and compliance are derived automatically.
12. Advanced users can configure the full supported provider API surface.
13. Users can work through CLI, IDE, natural language, or visual UI.
14. Deployment uses short-lived credentials and deterministic provider handlers.
15. State, history, drift, verification, and rollback limitations are accurately maintained.
16. Enterprise policies cannot be bypassed by AI or provider extensions.
17. Independent providers and implementations can pass conformance tests.
18. IIS can evolve through an open and controlled IEP process.
19. No application, IDE, cloud, AI model, or vendor owns the standard.
20. The ecosystem can become an implementation-independent standard for expressing infrastructure intent.

